  "prompt": "Is there anything faster than the speed of light?",
  "response": "According to our current understanding of physics, nothing with mass can travel faster than the speed of light in a vacuum, which is approximately 299,792,458 meters per second. This is a fundamental principle of Einstein's theory of special relativity.\n\nHowever, there are a few interesting phenomena related to this:\n\n1. Quantum entanglement: Particles can appear to communicate instantaneously, but this doesn't actually transfer information faster than light.\n\n2. Expansion of the universe: During the early universe, space itself expanded faster than the speed of light, but this doesn't violate relativity because space itself was stretching.\n\n3. Apparent superluminal motion: Some astronomical objects, like certain jets from black holes, can appear to move faster than light from our perspective, but this is an optical illusion.\n\n4. Tachyons: Hypothetical particles that might theoretically move faster than light, but they remain purely theoretical and have never been observed.\n\nAs of now, the speed of light remains the universal speed limit according to our best scientific understanding.",
